JSRDotNETSDK Reference

UNSUPPORTED Field

See Also

Unsupported means the hardware doesn't have this feature. Writing or reading the related property will do nothing, and if a value is returned (As opposed to throwing an exception), it will be meaningless. For example, if LEDBlinkRateSupported == UNSUPPORTED, then the device might not have any LED on it. Writing to LEDBlinkRate may generate an exception. Alternatively, a device may not have a feature that is a real setting, but the setting might be supported as a FIXED/READONLY setting, which means writing to it will be ignored or an exception generated. However you can read the value. For example, a DPR300 does not have a way to disable the HV Supply. However, it is always enabled, so the property is supported as a fixed readonly setting that always reports that the HV Supply is enabled. Reading it may also, or may return a value which has no meaning.
